TIER: T1
FILE: core/soil.py
AUTHOR: Shiva (Claude Code) + Sean Campbell

SUMMARY
-------
Initial implementation of SOIL — the inbound signal processing layer.

SOIL is the first contact layer. Raw input (files, text, events) enters here,
gets normalized into a standard Signal format, queued in soil.db, and drained
into LOAM for storage. SOIL has no opinions about what to do with signals —
it just receives, normalizes, and passes downstream.

DESIGN DECISIONS
----------------
1. Signal format: {signal_id, signal_type, source, content, category,
   username, received_at, status, metadata}
2. DB-backed queue (soil.db, caller provides path). Status: pending → ingested/failed.
3. watch_drop() — polls a drop directory for new files not yet queued.
   Polling (not inotify) for WSL compatibility.
4. drain() — processes pending signals → calls loam.ingest_full() for each.
   Returns count processed.
5. normalize() is stateless — converts raw input into a Signal dict.
   Caller can queue() it or discard it.
6. Category inference from file extension when not provided.
7. LOAM and VINE are optional deps — drain() degrades gracefully.

PUBLIC API
----------
init_tables(db_path) → None
normalize(source, content, signal_type, username, category=None, metadata=None) → dict
queue(db_path, signal) → str  # returns signal_id
drain(db_path, username, loam_db_path, vine_db_path=None,
      batch_size=10, llm_router=None) → int
watch_drop(db_path, username, drop_dir, extensions=None) → int  # files queued
pending(db_path, username, limit=20) → list[dict]
stats(db_path, username) → dict

SCHEMA
------
signals  — (signal_id TEXT PK, signal_type, source, content_path TEXT,
            category, username, received_at, status, metadata TEXT)

Note: content stored as file path or inline (<= 8KB). Large content written
to a sidecar file and content_path set. This keeps the queue table light.

GOVERNANCE: loam-initial-2026-03-03.applied (LOAM implemented — downstream dep)
